I can't show these to my friends who've never played the game because I know they'll think it looks stupid, leaving me to feel embarrassed.  I will have to wait for the movie to come out and generate some reviews before I consider spending my money on this.  Which is a shame because the Assassin's Creed games are among my favorite video games ever.

text: I'm REEEEAAAALY hoping they keep true to the historical references like the games did, but after seeing this, I'm having doubts that this movie will be anywhere near as satisfying as the games.  There's a ton of improvised weaponry in this trailer that is not historically accurate, which was the whole reason why they decided (for example) to not give Altair a crossbow in the first game like they originally intended. Crossbows did not exist in Syria during the 1100s, or the time of the Third Crusade.  The games expertly merge both fantasy with historical accuracy, and I'm not getting that feeling from this trailer. I guess we'll have to wait and see.

text: Anyone bitching about the music choice clearly doesn't understand the point of a trailer.  The music choice, especially in action films,  is about pacing, energy and punctuating the clips with high energy music. Orchestral Scores are entirely different from the Soundtrack. Some movies have soundtracks and scores that are genre matches, some have orchestral scores that are vastly different from the Soundtrack. a Soundtrack is music that accompanies the movie, it generally includes licensed or commissioned music for the movie. Sometimes it includes the score, sometimes not. The Score is the music that plays to enhance scenes and embellish the story.  On top of that trailers have been using top 40 music since trailers became a thing. In this case its a high action, fast cut trailer that isnt telling much of the story, its sole purpose is to showcase the action aspect of the film. It requires music to match it, modern pop/rock does that better than an orchestral score. Next will come a trailer likely showcasing more of the story which probably will include a different feel and musical accompaniment.  If your entire issue with this trailer is that its "music" doesnt match what you feel the trailer should have then it appears Ubisoft has done a good job with the rest of it. Seems like a lot of digging to find a reason to be salty.

text: Just came back from an early screening. I'm a big fan of the franchise, so I may be biased but I absolutely loved the film. I think, among fans of the franchise,  the viewing experience will greatly depend on how you look at the franchise.   Me, personally, think the present-timeline is an advantage and the heart of the franchise, rather than a weakness; therefore, I think putting emphasis on the present rather than the past is the right course of the franchise and of the film. However, I can see that those who are opposed to this notion will have a hard time of watching this film, as it jumps between timelines quickly.   I thought the film to have an engaging story, incredible action-sequences and aesthetics inspired by the games, wonderful music, wonderful cinematography and superb acting from the cast. It has everything to be a great film - and a great video-game inspired film at that - and it shouldn't be executed just yet by the critics. The real test of this film will be introducing the concepts and ideas of the game-franchise to the audience oblivious to the games and see how well it translates to their liking.

text: I like how they chose a timeline that historically excludes Muslim presence. They chose late 15th century, the period of the fall of Granada, the last Muslim bastion. I feel as if Hollywood wants to ignore Muslim history on purpose. Who ruled Spain before this films time line took place? For 850 years Muslims were dominant in Spain yet this film does not depict a single image of Muslims, as if Muslims never existed in Spain. Why does Western media censor Muslim history? Why hide it from the public? Further on, It's funny how they ignore Assassins creed's true historical backstory where it took place in the Levant, Syria and Jerusalem during the Crusades and the Hashahashins, the first true order of assassins and Altair and now conjure up some fallacy about a European Assassin order when we all know there were no European assassin orders, there were the Hashashshins and nobody else.

text: Ok I can't be the only one who enjoyed this movie right? Sure some of it was very Hollywood and at times it didn't make sense, but if you were a fan of the series and understood Abstergo and the whole Assassin's vs. Templars plot then it was not bad at all! They stayed true to the game in many aspects as well, there was a lot of hidden blade action, there was some free running, and some stealth and assassin chaos. I'd give the movie a solid 7/10 as an AC fan, I think that while it could have been better, it's very hard to get a movie based off of the games correctly but they did a good job of it.

text: Can someone please tell me why this film flopped?? I have only just seen it for the first time and I think it is an immensely fun and entertaining film that keeps true to the idea of the games... I did have low expectations due to other reviews but this is much better than the latest Tomb Raider film!! I really don't see why there is hate for it!! It maybe could have had more of a narrative but it has a beginning, middle, and end. I do not see why it has been given such a low score!! I really hope there will be a sequel! It deserves one!!
